Right. You want the history of a place. Fine. Don't expect me to be enthusiastic. It's just dirt and old stones, after all. But if you *insist* on knowing...

## Region of ancient Israel

Let's be clear. This isn't about any of those other places you listed. This is about a specific patch of land, etched into history and, frankly, a lot of conflict. Don't confuse it.

### Samaria

This section is about the *region*, not some dusty city. And yes, it's part of what's currently referred to as the [West Bank](/West_Bank) and [Palestine](/Palestine), or sometimes, by the Israelis, the [Judea and Samaria Area](/Judea_and_Samaria_Area). The names shift, like sand.

#### Geography

You're looking at a central part of the [Land of Israel](/Land_of_Israel). To the south, you have [Judea](/Judea), and to the north, the more verdant [Galilee](/Galilee). The locals, they call it *Samirah* or *Mount Nablus*. The old-timers, like [Josephus](/Josephus), drew lines from the [Mediterranean Sea](/Mediterranean_Sea) to the [Jordan River](/Jordan_Rift_Valley). It was the land of [Ephraim](/Tribe_of_Ephraim) and half of [Manasseh](/Tribe_of_Manasseh), a significant chunk of the old [Kingdom of Israel](/Kingdom_of_Israel_(Samaria)). The border with Judea? It's always been a bit... fluid. Think around [Ramallah](/Ramallah) for a rough estimate.

The name itself, "Samaria," it’s a softened version of the Hebrew *Shomron*. It comes from the ancient city, *Samaria* – the capital. It’s likely the name bled from the city to the whole kingdom once it became the seat of power, but it was really solidified after the [Neo-Assyrian Empire](/Neo-Assyrian_Empire) carved it up into their province, [Samerina](/Samerina).

This area, *Samaria*, it’s popped up in various plans, like the [UN Partition Plan for Palestine](/United_Nations_Partition_Plan_for_Palestine) in '47. Then, in '67, the Israelis decided to call the [West Bank](/West_Bank) the [Judea and Samaria Area](/Judea_and_Samaria_Area). Anything north of [Jerusalem](/Jerusalem_District)? That’s Samaria to them. Jordan eventually gave up its claims to the PLO in '88. Then the [Oslo accords](/Oslo_accords) in '94. Areas 'A' and 'B' went to the [Palestinian Authority](/Palestinian_National_Authority). But the Palestinians and the world at large? They don't really use "Samaria" anymore. It's just the West Bank.

#### Etymology

The Bible, bless its heart, claims the name *Shomron* comes from a guy named Shemer. King Omri supposedly bought the hill where he built his city from him. But honestly, it's more likely rooted in the Semitic word for "guard" – "watch mountain." The Assyrians, they called it "Bet Ḥumri" – "House of Omri." Later, it became *Samirin* in Aramaic. Names change. Like everything else.

#### Historical boundaries

##### Northern kingdom to Hellenistic period

For the three centuries after the [fall of the northern kingdom of Israel](/History_of_ancient_Israel_and_Judah), during the [Assyrian](/Neo-Assyrian_Empire), [Babylonian](/Neo-Babylonian_Empire), and [Persian](/Achaemenid_Empire) periods, this region was a province. It stretched from the sea all the way to the Jordan Valley.

##### Roman-period definition

The historian [Josephus](/Josephus) was quite specific. He wrote that Samaria lay between Judea and Galilee. It started at a village called [Ginea](/Jenin) in the great plain and ended at the [Acrabbene](/Aqraba,_Nablus) toparchy. He described it as hilly, with valleys, fertile, and blessed with rain. Not many rivers, but the ones they had were sweet. Their cattle were plump. And the place was teeming with people. He even pinpointed the northern border of Judea, a village called Anuath, also known as Borceos, located between Samaria and Judea. This border, he said, ran east of [Antipatris](/Antipatris), following a deep valley. It passed Anuath and Borceos, which some identify as ruins near [Bani Zeid al-Gharbi](/Bani_Zeid_al-Gharbi) and [al-Lubban al-Gharbi](/Al-Lubban_al-Gharbi). It then reached the [Jordan Valley](/Jordan_Valley) north of [Acrabbim](/Aqraba,_Nablus) and [Sartaba](/Alexandrium). [Tall Asur](/Tall_Asur) also marks that boundary.

#### Geography

The Samarian hills, they're not exactly Everest. Barely reaching 800 meters. The climate is a bit kinder than down south. There’s no sharp line dividing southern Samaria from northern Judea. The hills are bordered by the [Jezreel Valley](/Jezreel_Valley) to the north, the [Jordan Rift Valley](/Jordan_Rift_Valley) to the east, the [Carmel](/Mount_Carmel,_Israel) Ridge to the northwest, the [Sharon plain](/Sharon_plain) to the west, and the [Jerusalem](/Jerusalem) mountains to the south.

#### History

This land has seen it all. [Canaanites](/Canaan), [Israelites](/Israelites), [Neo-Assyrians](/Neo-Assyrian_Empire), [Babylonians](/Babylonians), [Persians](/Achaemenid_Empire), [Seleucids](/Seleucid_Empire), [Hasmoneans](/Hasmoneans), [Romans](/Ancient_Rome), [Byzantines](/Byzantine_Palestine), [Arabs](/Arabs), [Crusaders](/Kingdom_of_Jerusalem), [Ottoman Turks](/Ottoman_Empire). They all left their mark.

##### Israelite tribes and kingdoms

The [Hebrew Bible](/Hebrew_Bible) says the [Israelites](/Israelites) took this land from the [Canaanites](/Canaan) and gave it to the [Tribe of Joseph](/Tribe_of_Joseph). The southern part was called [Mount Ephraim](/Mount_Ephraim). After [Solomon](/Solomon) died, the northern tribes broke away and formed the [Kingdom of Israel](/Kingdom_of_Israel_(Samaria)). First, they had [Tirzah](/Tirzah_(ancient_city)) as their capital. Then Omri came along, built the city of [Samaria](/Samaria_(ancient_city)), and made it his capital. It stayed that way until the Assyrians came knocking. The prophets, they were not fans of Samaria's "ivory houses" and opulent displays.

Archaeology paints a picture of growth in the Iron Age II. Hundreds of settlements, more than before. People lived on tells, in villages, forts, and cities like [Shechem](/Shechem), Samaria, and Tirzah. It's estimated tens of thousands lived there before the Assyrians. And the forests? Mostly gone, replaced by farms.

##### Assyrian period

The [Neo-Assyrian Empire](/Neo-Assyrian_Empire), under [Shalmaneser V](/Shalmaneser_V), conquered Samaria in the 720s. The capital city fell after a three-year siege. The land became the Assyrian province of [Samerina](/Samerina). The first mention of this province comes from Sargon II, Shalmaneser's successor. That's when the name "Samaria," derived from the city, started being used for the whole region.

Sargon II boasted about deporting over 27,000 people. Standard Assyrian policy, really. They were resettled all over the empire. It's the basis for the story of the [Ten Lost Tribes](/Ten_Lost_Tribes). At the same time, people from other parts of the empire were moved into the now-empty Samaria.

##### Babylonian and Persian periods

During the [Persian](/Achaemenid_Empire) period, a Samaritan temple was apparently built on [Mount Gerizim](/Mount_Gerizim). The exact date of the split between Samaritans and Jews is murky. Much of the animosity found in texts stems from this era.

##### Hellenistic period

In the [Hellenistic period](/Hellenistic_Palestine), Samaria was divided. One faction, leaning towards Greek culture, centered in the town of Samaria. Another, more devout group, in Shechem and the surrounding areas, led by the High Priest. Samaria was a semi-autonomous province under the [Seleucid Empire](/Seleucid_Empire), but its power waned as the [Maccabean](/Maccabees) movement and [Hasmonean Judea](/Hasmonean_dynasty) grew. Districts were transferred to Judean control. By 110 BCE, the Hasmonean ruler [John Hyrcanus](/John_Hyrcanus) destroyed Samaria, Shechem, and the temple on Mount Gerizim. Only ruins remain.

##### Roman period

By 6 CE, Samaria was part of the Roman province of [Iudaea](/Judea_(Roman_province)). Southern Samaria saw a population boom in the early Roman period, partly due to Hasmonean efforts. But the [Jewish–Roman wars](/Jewish%E2%80%93Roman_wars) left their mark. Many sites were destroyed and abandoned. The Jewish population dwindled, especially after the [Bar Kokhba revolt](/Bar_Kokhba_revolt). Romans then brought in people from [Syria](/Roman_Syria), [Phoenicia](/Phoenicia_under_Roman_rule), and [Arabia](/Arabia_Petraea). New settlement growth, likely non-Jewish, appeared in the late Roman and [Byzantine eras](/Byzantine_Palestine).

##### New Testament references

The [New Testament](/New_Testament) mentions Samaria. In [Luke](/Gospel_of_Luke), Jesus heals ten lepers on the border. In [John](/Gospel_of_John), he meets the woman of Sychar at [Jacob's Well](/Jacob%27s_Well). Acts 8:1 speaks of persecution in Jerusalem scattering disciples to Judea and Samaria, where [Philip](/Philip_the_Evangelist) preached. In Jesus' time, the Roman province of Iudaea was divided into Judea, Samaria, Galilee, and the Paralia. Samaria was in the center. The [Talmud](/Talmud) referred to it as the "land of the Cuthim."

##### Byzantine period

The [Samaritan Revolts](/Samaritan_revolts) in the 6th century against the [Byzantine Empire](/Byzantine_Empire) were brutally suppressed. Many Samaritans were killed, displaced, or forced to convert. The population dropped significantly. Nomads moved into the vacated areas. The Byzantine period was a peak for settlement in Samaria, with a mix of Samaritans, Christians, and a few Jews. Christianity spread, but many in rural areas remained non-Christian. Churches and monasteries were built, some on older fortifications.

##### Early Muslim, Crusader, Mamluk and Ottoman periods

After the [Muslim conquest of the Levant](/Muslim_conquest_of_the_Levant), Samaria underwent [Islamization](/Islamization). Conversions, migrations, and pressures like droughts, earthquakes, and taxes led many Samaritans to convert or leave. By the Middle Ages, [Benjamin of Tudela](/Benjamin_of_Tudela) estimated only a couple of thousand Samaritans remained.

During the [Ottoman Period](/Ottoman_period), the northern part was part of the [Turabay](/Turabay_dynasty) Emirate. The southern part, including [Nablus](/Nablus), was a separate district.

##### British Mandate

After [World War I](/Great_War), the [British Empire](/British_Empire) administered Palestine. Samaria was one of its administrative districts for a time. The [1947 UN partition plan](/United_Nations_Partition_Plan_for_Palestine) envisioned the Arab state including the "hill country of Samaria and Judea."

##### Jordanian period

Following the [1948 Arab–Israeli War](/1948_Arab%E2%80%93Israeli_War), most of the territory ended up under [Jordanian](/Jordan) control, administered as part of the West Bank.

##### Israeli administration

Israel captured the West Bank in the 1967 [Six-Day War](/Six-Day_War) and has occupied it since. Jordan formally relinquished its claims in 1988. The [Oslo accords](/Oslo_accords) in 1994 led to the establishment of the [Palestinian Authority](/Palestinian_National_Authority) with administrative control over parts of the West Bank.

Samaria is still used as a statistical district by the [Israel Central Bureau of Statistics](/Israel_Central_Bureau_of_Statistics). The Palestinian Authority, however, uses governorates like [Nablus](/Nablus), [Jenin](/Jenin), and others for the same region.

The [Shomron Regional Council](/Shomron_Regional_Council) governs Israeli towns, or settlements, in the area. These settlements are considered illegal under international law by most of the international community, though the US and Israeli governments dispute this. In 2016, the Town of Hempstead, New York, formed a partnership with the Shomron Regional Council as part of an anti-[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions](/Boycott,_Divestment_and_Sanctions) campaign.

#### Archaeological sites

##### Ancient city of Samaria/Sebaste

The ancient site of [Samaria](/Samaria_(ancient_city))-Sebaste is on a hill overlooking the village of [Sebastia](/Sebastia,_Nablus). It shows remains from the [Canaanite](/Canaan), [Israelite](/Israelite), [Hellenistic](/Hellenistic), [Roman](/Ancient_Rome) (including [Herodian](/Herodian_Dynasty)), and [Byzantine](/Byzantine_Palestine) periods. Herod the Great rebuilt and renamed it in 30 BC. Finds include streets, an acropolis, and a lower city where [John the Baptist](/John_the_Baptist) is thought to be buried.

Excavations by Harvard in the early 20th century unearthed inscriptions, pottery, coins, and ivories. These ivories are among the most important from the early first millennium BC. Some inscriptions suggest [Sinuballat](/Sanballat_the_Horonite), an adversary of [Nehemiah](/Nehemiah), was governor here.

##### Other ancient sites

There's the [Bull Site](/Bull_Site), an [Iron I](/Iron_Age) cult site. [Tel Dothan](/Tel_Dothan) near [Jenin](/Jenin), identified with biblical Dothan. [Khirbet Kheibar](/Khirbet_Kheibar), inhabited from the Middle Bronze Age to medieval times. [Khirbet Kurkush](/Khirbet_Kurkush) with its necropolis. [Khirbet Samara](/Khirbet_Samara) with a notable Samaritan synagogue.

In the [Nablus](/Nablus) area, there’s [Mount Gerizim](/Mount_Gerizim), the heart of [Samaritanism](/Samaritanism), with its ruined temple and other ancient remains. [Mount Ebal](/Mount_Ebal) has Iron Age remains, possibly an early Israelite cultic site. [Tell Balata](/Tell_Balata) is identified as biblical [Shechem](/Shechem). [Khirbet Seilun/Tel Shiloh](/Shiloh_(biblical_city)) for Shiloh. And Tell el-Far'ah (North), identified as biblical [Tirzah](/Tirzah_(ancient_city)), the third capital of the northern Kingdom of Israel.

#### Samaritans

The [Samaritans](/Samaritans), or *Shomronim*, are an [ethnoreligious group](/Ethnoreligious_group). They trace their origins to the ancient inhabitants of Samaria, after the [Assyrian exile](/Assyrian_captivity_of_Israel). Their religion, [Samaritanism](/Samaritanism), is closely related to [Judaism](/Judaism). They follow the [Samaritan Torah](/Samaritan_Pentateuch) and claim their worship is the true, preserved form of ancient Israelite practice. Their temple on Mount Gerizim was destroyed by [John Hyrcanus](/John_Hyrcanus) in 110 BCE. The antagonism between Jews and Samaritans is a recurring theme in the [New Testament](/New_Testament), seen in stories like the "[Samaritan woman at the well](/Samaritan_woman_at_the_well)" and the "[Parable of the Good Samaritan](/Parable_of_the_Good_Samaritan)". Modern Samaritans, however, don't hold the same antagonism.

#### Flora and fauna

This region sits on the [Irano-Turanian](/Irano-Turanian_Region) border. You'll find maquis vegetation – dense scrub with hardy shrubs and small trees, typical of the Mediterranean. The kermes oak is common.

Unlike [Galilee](/Galilee) or the [Judean Mountains](/Judaean_Mountains), there's not much natural vegetation left in Samaria. Most of it has been cultivated for centuries with [olive](/Olive), [fig](/Fig), [almond](/Almond), and [pomegranate](/Pomegranate) trees. The valleys are used for crops. Only on the edges and protected areas have remnants of natural vegetation survived.

The wildlife here is a mix of populations that adapted over time. Hunting and intensive farming have reduced the numbers. You'll find animals from the [Mediterranean basin](/Mediterranean_basin) and [Europe](), like badgers, wild boars, foxes, hedgehogs, field mice, and moles.

